When my dad went over to the gulf the first time, I was very proud of him, more than proud, it increased the amount of respect I had for him as well.  Because of an older injury he can actually be in the regular troops, he's a supply officer, but he works hard at it, and he does a good job.  He's to old now to go to Iraq, but if he could I guarantee that he'd do it.  <br>
<br>
If I could go, I would.  In a heartbeat.  My dad taught me to shoot and I'm a damn good shot.  I'd join the marines and become a sniper if I could.  <br>
<br>
In any case, how many more 9/11's do you want to happen?  How 'bout a 9/11 but instead of a plane, they use a nuclear bomb at the super bowl, or in the middle of downtown LA?  The thing about nuclear weapons is that other than the first time we used them, no one who has them <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>wants</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to use them.  Saddam Hussein or Osama bin Laden would use one if they thought the opportunity was good enough.  Not only that, but any bomb they had would probably be an older one, and therefore a 'dirty' bomb, leaving the target location radioactive for the next thousand years.<br>
<br>
So where do you live?  The next time you think about dissing the armed forces in Iraq, imagine your neighborhood being a wasteland for the next eon, or about your muscles ripping themselves apart while your organs melt.....or if you survive, think about having the permanent side effects messing you up for the rest of your life.<br>
<br>
Oh, and if Iraq doesn't have chemical weapons, why are the Armed Forces finding counter agents?<br>
